"""
MKT Original Language Commentary — 1 John chapters 1–4
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-1john-1-4.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/1john.json
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json (G26, G166, G2434, G3875, G3306, G4151 — all contested)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/1john.json (MKT text for quoting)
- scripts/mkt-1john-1-3.py, scripts/mkt-1john-4-5.py (key translation decisions)

Key decisions in this range:
- G3306 (μένω): "abides/remains/lives in" — the connective tissue of John's theology;
  Greek present tense signals ongoing state, not momentary acts
- G26 (ἀγάπη): dispute_level 3 — willed, covenantal love distinct from φιλία;
  in 4:7-21 the letter's theology of love reaches its formal summit
- G2434 (ἱλασμός): "propitiation" not "expiation" — the forensic vs. cultic debate;
  appears only at 2:2 and 4:10 in 1 John
- G3875 (παράκλητος): "Advocate" in 2:1 — legal defense counsel, not comfort-giver;
  that nuance is reserved for the Spirit in the Gospel
- G4151 (πνεῦμα): capitalized "Spirit" for the Holy Spirit (3:24; 4:2,6,13);
  lowercase "spirit" for created or demonic spirits (4:1,3)
- G1343 (δικαιοσύνη): dispute_level 4 — "righteousness" throughout; in 3:7,10
  the MKT shifts to "right living" to surface the behavioral sense, but the root
  term is forensic in 2:29 (he is righteous → those born of him are righteous)
- Perfect verbs in ch. 1 (ἑωράκαμεν, ἀκηκόαμεν): past apostolic acts that carry
  forward as present claims — eyewitness testimony kept alive in writing
- σπέρμα (3:9): "God's seed" — the divine life-principle enabling the new birth;
  classification follows the three major readings (Spirit, Word, new nature)
- ἐν σαρκί (4:2): "in the flesh" — the Christological test targets proto-Docetic
  denial of the incarnation's physical reality
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOHN1 = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p><strong>ἀπ᾽ ἀρχῆς</strong> (<em>ap᾽ archēs</em>, "from the beginning") — the phrase lacks the article present in John 1:1 (<em>ἐν ἀρχῇ</em>), giving it a more absolute, primordial sense: not "from the beginning of this" but "from the origin of all things." The anaphora of four <em>ὅ</em> ("what") clauses — what we heard, saw, beheld, handled — builds cumulative weight before the subject is named.</p><p>Three Greek perfects govern the opening: <strong>ἀκηκόαμεν</strong> (we have heard), <strong>ἑωράκαμεν</strong> (we have seen), and implicitly the testimony stands (<em>μαρτυροῦμεν</em>, present). The perfect aspect signals past acts whose results remain in force — apostolic testimony is not merely historical memory but a living, present claim. The aorist <strong>ἐψηλάφησαν</strong> (our hands handled/touched) is deliberately physical, anchoring the testimony against any spiritualizing evasion.</p><p><strong>λόγου τῆς ζωῆς</strong> — "the Word of life." The genitive is probably appositional (the Word who is life) rather than objective (a word about life), echoing the Johannine Prologue, though here the physical handling of the Word is foregrounded rather than the pre-existent glory.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>ἐφανερώθη</strong> (<em>ephanerōthē</em>) — aorist passive of <em>φανερόω</em>, "was manifested." The verb appears twice in this verse, bookending the parenthetical testimony. It is a key term in 1 John (used again at 3:2,5,8; 4:9) and signals that what was hidden has been disclosed — not that something new came into being, but that what already existed became publicly visible.</p><p><strong>τὴν ζωὴν τὴν αἰώνιον</strong> — "the eternal life" (double article, emphatic). The definite article marks this not as a quality or concept but as a specific, identifiable reality that "was with the Father." The phrase <em>πρὸς τὸν πατέρα</em> ("with the Father") uses the same preposition as John 1:1 ("with God"), suggesting personal presence and relation rather than mere existence.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>κοινωνία</strong> (<em>koinōnia</em>, G2842) — rendered "fellowship" in the MKT, but the Greek root carries the sense of active sharing, partnership, and participation — more than social togetherness. The double occurrence ("fellowship with us... our fellowship is with the Father") maps the vertical and horizontal together: participation in the apostolic witness is simultaneously participation in the Father–Son relation.</p><p>The purpose clause <em>ἵνα καὶ ὑμεῖς κοινωνίαν ἔχητε μεθ᾽ ἡμῶν</em> — "so that you also may have fellowship with us" — places the Johannine community as the mediating link. The reader cannot bypass the apostolic witness to reach the divine fellowship directly.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>χαρά</strong> (<em>chara</em>) — "joy." The pronoun is contested: some manuscripts read <em>ἡμῶν</em> ("our joy") and others <em>ὑμῶν</em> ("your joy"). The MKT follows "our joy" — the community whose proclamation and whose readers\' reception together complete the joy of the eyewitnesses. <strong>πεπληρωμένη ᾖ</strong> — present perfect passive subjunctive: "may be (and remain) made full." Completeness of joy is the stated goal of writing, placing the letter\'s purpose within the tradition of Johannine joy language (cf. John 15:11; 16:24; 17:13).</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>θεὸς φῶς ἐστιν</strong> — "God is light." The predicate noun <em>φῶς</em> (light) is anarthrous — it identifies the character of God without reducing him to an abstraction. In Greek predicate-noun constructions, the anarthrous noun specifies the category or quality; the subject retains its definite identity. The statement is absolute: not "God is like light" or "God gives light" but "God = light" in his essential character.</p><p><strong>σκοτία ἐν αὐτῷ οὐκ ἔστιν οὐδεμία</strong> — the double negative is emphatic: "darkness in him is not, not even any." The MKT renders "no darkness at all," correctly capturing the intensified negation. Darkness is not a partial condition or a limited defect — it is utterly absent.</p>',
    "6": '<p>This verse opens the first of six <em>ἐὰν εἴπωμεν</em> ("if we say") conditions in chapters 1–2 (1:6,8,10; 2:4,6,9). Each pairs a false verbal claim with a behavioral reality that contradicts it. The present tense <strong>περιπατῶμεν ἐν τῇ σκοτίᾳ</strong> — "we walk in darkness" — signals habitual, ongoing conduct, not isolated acts.</p><p><strong>ψευδόμεθα</strong> — present "we lie," not "we were mistaken." The verdict is active moral falsehood. <strong>οὐ ποιοῦμεν τὴν ἀλήθειαν</strong> — "we do not do (practice) the truth." In Johannine usage, truth is not merely believed but enacted — a behavioral category as much as an epistemic one.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>ἐν τῷ φωτί ... ὡς αὐτός ἐστιν ἐν τῷ φωτί</strong> — "in the light as he himself is in the light." The comparison does not flatten the distinction: God is the source of light; believers walk <em>in</em> it. The condition is ongoing present-tense walking, not a one-time entry.</p><p><strong>καθαρίζει ἡμᾶς ἀπὸ πάσης ἁμαρτίας</strong> — <em>καθαρίζει</em> is present tense: ongoing, continuous cleansing. The blood of Jesus his Son is not a past judicial act only but an ever-present purifying reality. <em>πάσης ἁμαρτίας</em> — "all sin" (singular), the sin-condition as a whole, not merely individual transgressions. Fellowship with one another and cleansing are not sequential but simultaneous results of walking in the light.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>ἁμαρτίαν οὐκ ἔχομεν</strong> — "we have no sin." The claim is about possessing or carrying sin as a present condition, not about committing specific sinful acts (contrast v.10, "we have not sinned"). The present-tense <strong>πλανῶμεν</strong> — "we deceive" — is reflexive: the deception is self-directed. <strong>ἡ ἀλήθεια οὐκ ἔστιν ἐν ἡμῖν</strong> — "the truth is not in us." <em>Truth</em> (ἡ ἀλήθεια, with article) is not a proposition but a living reality with personal character in Johannine usage.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>ἐὰν ὁμολογῶμεν τὰς ἁμαρτίας</strong> — <em>ὁμολογέω</em> means literally "to say the same thing" — to agree with God\'s verdict about one\'s sin rather than rationalizing it. The present tense suggests an ongoing posture of truthfulness before God, not a once-for-all act.</p><p><strong>πιστός ἐστιν καὶ δίκαιος</strong> — "he is faithful and just (righteous)." Two distinct attributes ground the promise. <em>Πιστός</em> (faithful): God\'s covenant commitment guarantees the forgiveness. <em>Δίκαιος</em> (righteous/just): the forgiveness is not a legal irregularity but grounded in the atoning work already accomplished. <strong>ἵνα ἀφῇ ἡμῖν τὰς ἁμαρτίας καὶ καθαρίσῃ ἡμᾶς ἀπὸ πάσης ἀδικίας</strong> — the two aorist subjunctives: <em>ἀφῇ</em> (forgive, complete act) and <em>καθαρίσῃ</em> (cleanse, complete act). Both together constitute the full response to confession.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>ἡμαρτήκαμεν</strong> — perfect "we have sinned" — not the present sinful condition of v.8 but the denial of specific, completed sinful acts: claiming a clean record, not merely a clean present state. <strong>ψεύστην ποιοῦμεν αὐτόν</strong> — "we make him a liar" — the charge against God himself, not merely an error. The claim that one has never sinned directly contradicts the divine testimony. <strong>ὁ λόγος αὐτοῦ οὐκ ἔστιν ἐν ἡμῖν</strong> — "his word is not in us" — an absence of indwelling personal reality, not merely intellectual disagreement.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "1": '<p><strong>τεκνία</strong> (<em>teknia</em>, G5040) — "my little children," a tender diminutive used only by John in the NT (seven times in 1 John, once in John 13:33). Distinct from <em>παιδία</em> (G3813, children generally). The MKT renders both "dear children."</p><p><strong>παράκλητον ἔχομεν</strong> — "we have an Advocate." <em>Παράκλητος</em> (G3875) is a forensic term — one called alongside to defend; in Attic Greek, a legal advocate who speaks on behalf of the accused. In the Gospel of John (14:16,26; 15:26; 16:7), the same term is applied to the Spirit as Comforter/Helper, but here it is Jesus functioning as defense counsel before the heavenly court. <strong>δίκαιον</strong> — "the Righteous One." His righteous standing before the Father qualifies him to intercede; only the righteous can advocate effectively in a court of righteousness.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>ἱλασμός</strong> (<em>hilasmos</em>, G2434) — appears in the NT only at 2:2 and 4:10. The word has two competing definitions: (1) <em>propitiation</em> — a sacrifice that turns away divine wrath by satisfying the offended party; (2) <em>expiation</em> — a sacrifice that covers or removes sin. The propitiation reading fits the Johannine context: v.1 establishes the Father as the party before whom Jesus pleads, and the legal/forensic frame of the passage implies an offended justice being satisfied, not merely an unclean object being covered.</p><p><strong>περὶ ὅλου τοῦ κόσμου</strong> — "for the sins of the whole world." The scope is universal: John does not say the atonement was numerically applied to all, but that the sacrifice is sufficient for and directed toward the entire world, not only the covenant community.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>ἐγνώκαμεν αὐτόν</strong> — perfect of <em>γινώσκω</em>: "we have come to know him" — a completed past event (the initial knowing) whose result (the ongoing knowledge) stands. This contrasts with the claim of v.4 (<em>ἔγνωκα αὐτόν</em>, also perfect but boasted without corresponding behavior). Both verses use the same form; the difference lies in the behavioral evidence John requires. <strong>ἐὰν τὰς ἐντολὰς αὐτοῦ τηρῶμεν</strong> — <em>τηρέω</em> (G5083) = to guard, maintain, observe — not merely to obey once but to hold in custody. Present subjunctive implies habitual keeping.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>ψεύστης</strong> — "a liar." The word is blunt and judicial. In 1 John, <em>ψεύστης</em> is applied to those who deny the Son (2:22), those who claim to love God while hating their brother (4:20), and here to those whose verbal claim of knowing Christ is contradicted by behavior. The category is not "mistaken" but "falsifying." <strong>ἡ ἀλήθεια ἐν τούτῳ οὐκ ἔστιν</strong> — truth as a living indwelling reality, absent from this person (cf. 1:8 and 1:10).</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>ὃς δ᾽ ἂν τηρῇ αὐτοῦ τὸν λόγον</strong> — "but whoever keeps his word." The shift from <em>ἐντολάς</em> (commandments, plural, vv.3-4) to <em>λόγον</em> (word, singular) is significant: keeping the word is keeping the total message, not merely rule-following. <strong>ἀληθῶς ἐν τούτῳ ἡ ἀγάπη τοῦ θεοῦ τετελείωται</strong> — "the love of God has been truly perfected in this person." <em>Τετελείωται</em>: perfect passive of <em>τελειόω</em> — "has been brought to its goal." <em>Ἀγάπη τοῦ θεοῦ</em> — the genitive is probably subjective (God\'s love reaching its intended expression in us), though both readings are grammatically possible.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>ὁ λέγων ἐν αὐτῷ μένειν</strong> — "the one who says he abides in him." <em>Μένω</em> (G3306) in 1 John is not static dwelling but dynamic staying — choosing continually to remain in the relationship. The one who claims this abiding <strong>ὀφείλει... περιπατεῖν</strong> — "is obligated to walk." <em>Ὀφείλω</em> (G3784) is a term of moral debt: not "it would be nice" but "owes it."</p><p><strong>καθὼς ἐκεῖνος περιεπάτησεν</strong> — "just as that one walked." The Greek <em>ἐκεῖνος</em> (that one) is a demonstrative pronoun John uses specifically for Jesus in elevated, almost confessional contexts (3:3,5,7,16; 4:17). The aorist <em>περιεπάτησεν</em> summarizes Jesus\' entire earthly life as a completed pattern for imitation.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>ἀγαπητοί</strong> (<em>agapētoi</em>) — "Beloved." The word is the adjective form of <em>ἀγάπη</em>, meaning those who are loved — not merely friends by social circumstance but those within the embrace of covenant love. <strong>ἐντολὴν παλαιάν</strong> — <em>παλαιός</em> (G3820) = old in the sense of long-standing, ancient. The old command (love one another) dates from "the beginning" — probably the beginning of the community\'s reception of the gospel, not creation. The old command <em>is</em> the message they heard — obedience is tied to the original proclamation.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>ἐντολὴν καινήν</strong> — the same commandment is also <em>new</em>. <em>Καινός</em> (G2537) = new in quality or character, not merely recent — as distinct from <em>νέος</em> (new in time). The newness is demonstrated by its truth being realized: <strong>ὅ ἐστιν ἀληθὲς ἐν αὐτῷ καὶ ἐν ὑμῖν</strong> — "which is true in him and in you." The command has proved itself real in Christ\'s life and is now proving itself real in the readers\' community. <strong>ἡ σκοτία παράγεται καὶ τὸ φῶς τὸ ἀληθινόν ἤδη φαίνει</strong> — present tenses: "the darkness is passing away, and the true light is already shining." The command\'s newness rests on the eschatological overlap: the light is already present.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The construction mirrors v.4: a false claim (<em>ὁ λέγων</em>, "the one who says") confronted by behavioral contradiction. <strong>ἕως ἄρτι</strong> — "until now/still." Even now, in the age of the already-shining light, this person remains in darkness. The present-tense <strong>ἐστίν</strong> is emphatic: regardless of any verbal claim, this is their present location.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>ὁ ἀγαπῶν τὸν ἀδελφὸν αὐτοῦ ἐν τῷ φωτί μένει</strong> — "the one who loves his brother abides in the light." Love is the evidence of being in the light — not the cause of it, but the proof. <strong>σκάνδαλον ἐν αὐτῷ οὐκ ἔστιν</strong> — "there is no stumbling block in him." <em>Σκάνδαλον</em> (G4625): originally the trigger of a trap; here, what would cause another to fall. The love-abider is safe not only for themselves but for others.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The one who hates is located in three consecutive darkness phrases: <em>ἐν τῇ σκοτίᾳ ἐστίν</em> (is in the darkness), <em>ἐν τῇ σκοτίᾳ περιπατεῖ</em> (walks in the darkness), <em>οὐκ οἶδεν ποῦ ὑπάγει</em> (does not know where he is going). The triple pattern is rhetorical — each clause reinforces total disorientation. <strong>ἡ σκοτία ἐτύφλωσεν τοὺς ὀφθαλμοὺς αὐτοῦ</strong> — "the darkness has blinded his eyes" (aorist — a completed blinding). The hater has been rendered unable to find a way out.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Verses 12–14 form a structured threefold address (children, fathers, young men), repeated at vv.13b-14. <strong>ἀφέωνται ὑμῖν αἱ ἁμαρτίαι</strong> — "your sins have been forgiven" (perfect passive — a past event with present standing). <strong>διὰ τὸ ὄνομα αὐτοῦ</strong> — "on account of his name." The name carries the full identity and authority of the person; forgiveness is mediated through the specific person of Jesus, not an abstract principle.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>τὸν ἀπ᾽ ἀρχῆς</strong> — "him who is from the beginning." The fathers have known the pre-existent one — echoing 1:1. The depth of their knowing is proportioned to the duration of the relationship with the one who is eternally prior. <strong>τὸν πονηρόν</strong> (G4190, "the evil one") — with article, a personal referent: Satan, not abstract evil. The young men have "overcome" (<em>νενικήκατε</em>, perfect) the personal adversary — a completed victory that stands.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The tense shifts from γράφω (present "I write," vv.12-13a) to ἔγραψα (aorist "I wrote," vv.13b-14). This is the <em>epistolary aorist</em> — the author writes from the future perspective of the reader, who will receive it as a past communication. It is not a reference to a different earlier letter. <strong>ὁ λόγος τοῦ θεοῦ ἐν ὑμῖν μένει</strong> — "the word of God abides in you." The word is not merely known but dwelling (μένω, present) — the same indwelling language applied to God himself in later chapters.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>μὴ ἀγαπᾶτε τὸν κόσμον</strong> — present imperative with negation: "do not make a habit of loving the world." <em>Κόσμος</em> (G2889) — in Johannine usage, the world as organized in opposition to God, not the creation per se (cf. 4:9 where God loves the world and 4:14 where the Son is Savior of the world). <strong>ἡ ἀγάπη τοῦ πατρός</strong> — "the love of the Father" — whether objective (our love for the Father) or subjective (the Father\'s love flowing in us) — is incompatible with world-love. The verb <em>ἀγαπάω</em> is the same for both loves; the objects define the incompatibility.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Three elements of the <em>κόσμος</em>: (1) <strong>ἡ ἐπιθυμία τῆς σαρκός</strong> — desire generated by the bodily/fallen nature; (2) <strong>ἡ ἐπιθυμία τῶν ὀφθαλμῶν</strong> — desire triggered by what is seen and coveted; (3) <strong>ἡ ἀλαζονεία τοῦ βίου</strong> — the arrogant display (<em>ἀλαζονεία</em>, G212) of material possessions and status (<em>βίος</em> = material means of living, distinct from <em>ζωή</em> = spiritual life). All three <em>οὐκ ἔστιν ἐκ τοῦ πατρός</em> — "is not from the Father." The preposition <em>ἐκ</em> traces origin: these are not God-originated desires.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>ὁ κόσμος παράγεται</strong> — "the world is passing away" (present, ongoing). The same verb as 2:8 — the darkness also is passing. Both the cosmos and its craving are in the process of dissolution. <strong>ὁ δὲ ποιῶν τὸ θέλημα τοῦ θεοῦ μένει εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα</strong> — "the one who does the will of God abides into the age." <em>Εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα</em> = "forever" (literally "into the age"). The contrast is stark: the world and its craving are transient; the God-doer has the permanence of divine life.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>ἐσχάτη ὥρα ἐστίν</strong> — "it is the last hour." The phrase is anarthrous and unique to 1 John in the NT. It does not require a short time frame — in Johannine eschatology the "hour" has already "come" (John 5:25; 16:2,32) while still arriving. <strong>ἀντίχριστος</strong> (G500) — "antichrist" as both the coming figure (singular, end-time adversary) and as present realized threat (many antichrists, plural). John is the only NT author to use the term; the plural use here indicates that the spirit of antichrist is already embodied in specific false teachers in the community.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>ἐξ ἡμῶν ἐξῆλθαν</strong> — "they went out from us." The departure itself is the evidence. <strong>ἀλλ᾽ οὐκ ἦσαν ἐξ ἡμῶν</strong> — "but they were not of us." The preposition <em>ἐκ</em> (of, from) identifies origin and therefore belonging: to be <em>of</em> the community is to belong to it constitutively, not just numerically. <strong>εἰ γὰρ ἐξ ἡμῶν ἦσαν, μεμενήκεισαν ἂν μεθ᾽ ἡμῶν</strong> — a second-class conditional (contrary to fact): they were not of us, therefore they did not remain. The departure was a disclosure, not a surprise.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>χρῖσμα</strong> (<em>chrisma</em>, G5545) — "anointing." This noun appears in the NT only at 1 John 2:20,27. Related to <em>χριστός</em> (the Anointed One), the <em>chrisma</em> believers receive is from "the Holy One" (<em>ὁ ἅγιος</em>) — probably Christ, though some identify God the Father. The anointing likely refers to the Spirit given at conversion, constituting a counter-parallel to the false teachers\' claimed special knowledge.</p><p><strong>οἴδατε πάντες</strong> — "you all know." Preferred over <em>πάντα</em> ("you know all things"): the contrast is between the sectarians who claim elite gnosis and the community that <em>all</em> possess genuine knowing.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The verse gives the ground for writing: not ignorance but existing knowledge. <strong>πᾶν ψεῦδος ἐκ τῆς ἀληθείας οὐκ ἔστιν</strong> — "every lie is not from the truth." The double negative pattern is emphatic: no lie whatsoever has its origin in the truth. Lie and truth have different sources (<em>ἐκ</em>), not different qualities of the same stream.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>ψεύστης</strong> revisited. The supreme <em>liar</em> is the one who denies the central christological claim: <strong>ὁ ἀρνούμενος ὅτι Ἰησοῦς οὐκ ἔστιν ὁ Χριστός</strong> — "the one who denies that Jesus is the Christ." The denial has structural consequences: <strong>οὗτός ἐστιν ὁ ἀντίχριστος ὁ ἀρνούμενος τὸν πατέρα καὶ τὸν υἱόν</strong> — to deny the Son is simultaneously to deny the Father. The Father–Son relation is not separable: one cannot hold the Father while rejecting the Son.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>πᾶς ὁ ἀρνούμενος τὸν υἱὸν οὐδὲ τὸν πατέρα ἔχει</strong> — "everyone who denies the Son does not even have the Father." <em>Ἔχω</em> here = possessing in a relational sense. The logic is tight: the Father is accessible only through the Son. <strong>ὁ ὁμολογῶν τὸν υἱὸν καὶ τὸν πατέρα ἔχει</strong> — "the one who confesses the Son has the Father also." <em>Ὁμολογέω</em> here: not just affirming truth but openly declaring allegiance — a public, verbal act.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>ὑμεῖς ὃ ἠκούσατε ἀπ᾽ ἀρχῆς</strong> — the appeal to "what you heard from the beginning" returns to the letter\'s opening framework (1:1). The readers\' anchor is apostolic testimony received at conversion, not new revelations from departing teachers. <strong>ἐν ὑμῖν μενέτω</strong> — imperative: "let it remain in you." The readers are commanded to ensure the message stays in residence.</p><p><strong>ἐν τῷ υἱῷ καὶ ἐν τῷ πατρί μενεῖτε</strong> — "you will remain in the Son and in the Father." The conditional structure: if the message abides in them, they will abide in the divine persons. Doctrinal faithfulness and relational indwelling are inseparable in Johannine theology.</p>',
    "25": '<p><strong>ἡ ἐπαγγελία ἥν αὐτὸς ἐπηγγείλατο ἡμῖν</strong> — "the promise that he himself promised us." The cognate accusative construction (<em>ἐπαγγελία ... ἐπηγγείλατο</em>) emphasizes the directness: this is exactly what he committed to. <strong>τὴν ζωὴν τὴν αἰώνιον</strong> — "the eternal life" (definite article, as in 1:2). The promise returns to the letter\'s opening — the eternal life that was with the Father and was manifested is now the promised destination for those who remain.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A transitional verse explaining the foregoing polemic. <strong>τῶν πλανώντων ὑμᾶς</strong> — "those who lead you astray" (<em>πλανάω</em>, G4105): those who cause to wander. The language of deception and wandering frames the false teachers\' activity throughout 1 John. John writes not to correct ignorance but to arm against active, ongoing deceivers.</p>',
    "27": '<p><strong>τὸ χρῖσμα ὃ ἐλάβετε ἀπ᾽ αὐτοῦ μένει ἐν ὑμῖν</strong> — "the anointing which you received from him remains in you." Present tense <em>μένει</em>: the anointing\'s abiding is ongoing. <strong>οὐ χρείαν ἔχετε ἵνα τις διδάσκῃ ὑμᾶς</strong> — "you have no need that anyone teach you." This is not anti-teaching in general (the letter itself teaches!) but specifically directed against the secessionists\' claim to exclusive enlightenment. The anointing itself — the Spirit — is the universal teacher of the community.</p><p><strong>ψεῦδός ἐστιν καὶ οὐκ ἔστιν ψεῦδος</strong> — "it is true and is not a lie." The anointing\'s truth is confirmed by its self-consistency with the original message.</p>',
    "28": '<p><strong>νῦν, τεκνία, μένετε ἐν αὐτῷ</strong> — "now, dear children, abide in him." The imperative <em>μένετε</em> pulls together the abiding theme of the chapter. <strong>ἵνα ἐὰν φανερωθῇ σχῶμεν παρρησίαν</strong> — "so that when he is revealed we may have boldness." <em>Παρρησία</em> (G3954): literally "all-speech" — the freedom of unrestricted speech, here the eschatological confidence of the community at the parousia, contrasted with <strong>αἰσχυνθῶμεν ἀπ᾽ αὐτοῦ</strong> — "shrink in shame from him." The verb <em>αἰσχύνω</em> connotes the social shame of public exposure.</p>',
    "29": '<p><strong>ἐὰν εἰδῆτε ὅτι δίκαιός ἐστιν</strong> — "if you know that he is righteous." The condition is not in doubt; the <em>ἐάν</em> introduces an inference. <strong>γινώσκετε ὅτι πᾶς ὁ ποιῶν τὴν δικαιοσύνην ἐξ αὐτοῦ γεγέννηται</strong> — "know that everyone who practices righteousness has been born of him." <em>Γεγέννηται</em>: perfect passive of <em>γεννάω</em> — "has been born" — a past completed act with present standing. The new birth is the ground of righteous practice; practice is the evidence of birth, not its cause. This verse bridges chapter 2 to chapter 3\'s extended development of the born-of-God theme.</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "1": '<p><strong>ποταπὴν ἀγάπην</strong> — "what kind of love." <em>Ποταπός</em> (G4217) originally meant "from what country" and carried the sense of something astonishing or alien to ordinary experience — not merely "how great" but "how categorically different." <strong>δεδώκαμεν</strong> — perfect "has lavished/given" — the Father\'s act of naming us as children is a completed gift with present standing.</p><p><strong>διὰ τοῦτο ὁ κόσμος οὐ γινώσκει ἡμᾶς</strong> — "for this reason the world does not know us." The world\'s failure to recognize believers is not social rejection but epistemological: it did not know the Father (present tense — ongoing), so it cannot recognize the Father\'s family characteristics in believers.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>ἀγαπητοί, νῦν τέκνα θεοῦ ἐσμεν</strong> — "Beloved, we are now children of God." The present-tense status is emphatic: divine sonship is not only future. <strong>καὶ οὔπω ἐφανερώθη τί ἐσόμεθα</strong> — "and what we will be has not yet been manifested." The verb <em>φανερόω</em> (appear, manifest) recurs from 1:2 — the same verb used of Christ\'s incarnate appearance is now applied to the believers\' eschatological disclosure.</p><p><strong>ὅτι ὀψόμεθα αὐτὸν καθώς ἐστιν</strong> — "because we shall see him as he is." The <em>ὅτι</em> (because) gives the causal ground for transformation: the beatific vision itself produces the likeness. The future <em>ὀψόμεθα</em> implies that no present, partial vision is identical to this eschatological sight.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>ἁγνίζει ἑαυτόν</strong> — "purifies himself." <em>Ἁγνίζω</em> (G48) — to make pure; related to <em>ἅγιος</em> (holy) but with emphasis on the moral purity that distinguishes what is consecrated. The active voice and reflexive <em>ἑαυτόν</em>: the believer participates in their own purification — the hope motivates a present ethical response. <strong>καθὼς ἐκεῖνος ἁγνός ἐστιν</strong> — "just as that one is pure." <em>Ἐκεῖνος</em> — John\'s elevated demonstrative for Christ (see 2:6). Present-tense <em>ἐστίν</em>: Christ\'s purity is his ongoing state, the standard being aimed at.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>ἡ ἁμαρτία ἐστὶν ἡ ἀνομία</strong> — "sin is lawlessness." The equation is total: not merely that lawlessness is a type of sin, but that sin in its essence is <em>ἀνομία</em> (G458, lawlessness — absence of or contempt for law). The article makes this a predicate identification. This is not primarily a statement about rule-breaking but about a disposition of rebellion against the divine ordering of reality.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>ἐφανερώθη</strong> — "was manifested" (aorist passive). The appearance of Christ serves a specific purpose: <strong>ἵνα τὰς ἁμαρτίας ἄρῃ</strong> — "to take away sins." <em>Αἴρω</em> (G142, aorist subjunctive here) = to lift, carry away — not merely to cover or forgive but to remove. The same verb appears in John 1:29 ("Behold, the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world"). <strong>ἁμαρτία ἐν αὐτῷ οὐκ ἔστιν</strong> — "in him there is no sin" (anarthrous, emphatic). His sinlessness is the ground for his sin-removing work.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>πᾶς ὁ ἐν αὐτῷ μένων οὐχ ἁμαρτάνει</strong> — "everyone who abides in him does not sin." Both <em>μένων</em> (abiding) and <em>ἁμαρτάνει</em> (sins) are present participle and present indicative — ongoing states. The claim is about habitual pattern, not sinless perfection (cf. 1:8-10). The one whose characteristic mode of existence is abiding does not have sin as their characteristic mode of existence.</p><p><strong>πᾶς ὁ ἁμαρτάνων οὐχ ἑώρακεν αὐτὸν οὐδὲ ἔγνωκεν αὐτόν</strong> — "everyone who sins has not seen him nor known him." Perfect tenses: the absence of genuine past experience of Christ is evidenced in the present pattern of sin.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>μηδεὶς πλανάτω ὑμᾶς</strong> — "let no one lead you astray." Present imperative of <em>πλανάω</em> — the same verb as 2:26 (<em>πλανώντων</em>). The danger is ongoing. <strong>ὁ ποιῶν τὴν δικαιοσύνην δίκαιός ἐστιν</strong> — "the one who does righteousness is righteous." Greek identifies the person by their practice: there is no righteousness status that exists apart from righteous practice. <em>Δικαιοσύνη</em> (G1343, dispute_level 4) — here in its behavioral sense (right-living), though the forensic root (righteous standing before God) underlies it.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>ὁ ποιῶν τὴν ἁμαρτίαν ἐκ τοῦ διαβόλου ἐστίν</strong> — "the one who does sin is of the devil." <em>Ἐκ</em> (of/from) designates origin and allegiance: to practice sin is to act from the devil\'s side of the cosmic divide. <strong>ὅτι ἀπ᾽ ἀρχῆς ὁ διάβολος ἁμαρτάνει</strong> — "because the devil has been sinning from the beginning." Present tense: continuous sinning from the primordial point — the devil is defined by what he has done without interruption since his origin.</p><p><strong>εἰς τοῦτο ἐφανερώθη ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ θεοῦ</strong> — "for this purpose the Son of God was manifested." <em>Ἐφανερώθη</em> (aorist passive, φανερόω) — the same verb as 1:2; 3:5. The incarnate appearance has a stated destructive purpose: <strong>ἵνα λύσῃ τὰ ἔργα τοῦ διαβόλου</strong> — "to destroy the works of the devil." <em>Λύω</em> (G3089) = to loose, dissolve, destroy. The works are structural — not merely overcome but dismantled.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>πᾶς ὁ γεγεννημένος ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ ἁμαρτίαν οὐ ποιεῖ</strong> — "everyone who has been born of God does not practice sin." <em>Γεγεννημένος</em>: perfect passive participle — "the one who has been born" — the birth is a completed, ongoing state. The sinning (<em>ποιεῖ</em>, present) that is denied is habitual practice.</p><p><strong>ὅτι σπέρμα αὐτοῦ ἐν αὐτῷ μένει</strong> — "because his seed remains in him." <em>Σπέρμα</em> (G4690): the "seed" of God. Three main interpretations exist: (1) the divine nature itself; (2) the Holy Spirit as agent of new birth; (3) the word of God as instrument of regeneration (cf. James 1:18; 1 Pet 1:23). All three find support in Johannine theology; the term may be deliberately polyvalent. The point: the divine generative principle abides (<em>μένει</em>, present) in the born-of-God person, making sin-as-lifestyle impossible.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>ἐν τούτῳ φανερά ἐστιν τὰ τέκνα τοῦ θεοῦ καὶ τὰ τέκνα τοῦ διαβόλου</strong> — "in this the children of God and the children of the devil are manifest." <em>Φανερός</em> (evident, visible) uses the <em>phan-</em> root running through the letter. The two families become visible by their characteristic practices. The criteria are twofold: <em>δικαιοσύνη</em> (righteousness) and <em>ἀγάπη τοῦ ἀδελφοῦ</em> (love of the brother). Neither alone suffices; together they constitute the distinguishing mark.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>ἀγγελία</strong> (<em>angelia</em>, G31) — "message," appearing only here and at 1:5 in the NT. The letter frames its two great declarations as <em>messages</em> received and transmitted: "God is light" (1:5) and "we should love one another" (3:11). Both are sourced in apostolic proclamation from the beginning — not new revelations but original announcements. <strong>ἀπ᾽ ἀρχῆς</strong> — "from the beginning" — the same phrase as 1:1, 2:7,13,14,24.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>Κάιν</strong> — Cain appears only here in the NT epistles as a type (Heb 11:4 mentions Abel). <strong>ἐκ τοῦ πονηροῦ ἦν</strong> — "was of the evil one" (<em>ἐκ</em>, origin/allegiance). <strong>ἔσφαξεν</strong> (G4969) — "slew/slaughtered." The verb is used in Revelation for the slaughter of the Lamb — a pointed contrast with the lamb whose blood cleanses. <strong>χάριν τίνος ἔσφαξεν αὐτόν</strong> — "for what reason did he slaughter him?" John answers: <strong>ὅτι τὰ ἔργα αὐτοῦ πονηρὰ ἦν τὰ δὲ τοῦ ἀδελφοῦ αὐτοῦ δίκαια</strong> — "because his works were evil and his brother\'s were righteous." Righteousness provokes murderous hatred in those whose origin is the evil one.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>μὴ θαυμάζετε</strong> — "do not be surprised/marvel" (present imperative with negation). World hatred of believers is not anomalous but structurally predictable: Cain established the pattern. <strong>εἰ μισεῖ ὑμᾶς ὁ κόσμος</strong> — "if the world hates you." The <em>εἰ</em> + indicative is a first-class condition — the reality of the world\'s hatred is assumed, not hypothetical.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>ἡμεῖς οἴδαμεν</strong> — "we know" (<em>οἶδα</em>, the know-by-perception verb). <strong>μεταβεβήκαμεν ἐκ τοῦ θανάτου εἰς τὴν ζωήν</strong> — "we have passed from death into life." Perfect tense: the crossing is a completed act with permanent result — not "we are passing" but "we have crossed." The evidence: <strong>ὅτι ἀγαπῶμεν τοὺς ἀδελφούς</strong> — "because we love the brothers and sisters." The love is evidence, not cause, of the transfer. <strong>ὁ μὴ ἀγαπῶν μένει ἐν τῷ θανάτῳ</strong> — "the one who does not love remains in death." <em>Μένει</em> — present, ongoing residence in death\'s domain.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>πᾶς ὁ μισῶν τὸν ἀδελφὸν αὐτοῦ ἀνθρωποκτόνος ἐστίν</strong> — "everyone who hates his brother is a murderer." The move from Cain\'s external act to the internal disposition reflects Jesus\' logic in Matt 5:21-22, now formalized as a categorical identification. <em>Ἀνθρωποκτόνος</em> (G443) = man-killer; the same word used in John 8:44 for the devil. <strong>οὐδεὶς ἀνθρωποκτόνος ἔχει ζωὴν αἰώνιον ἐν αὐτῷ μένουσαν</strong> — "no murderer has eternal life remaining in him." <em>Μένουσαν</em> — present participle: the life does not have residence there.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>ἐν τούτῳ ἐγνώκαμεν τὴν ἀγάπην</strong> — "by this we have come to know love." <em>Ἐγνώκαμεν</em>: perfect of <em>γινώσκω</em> — we have come to know and continue to know. The object is not a concept but a reality disclosed by a specific historical act. <strong>ὅτι ἐκεῖνος ὑπὲρ ἡμῶν τὴν ψυχὴν αὐτοῦ ἔθηκεν</strong> — "because that one laid down his life for us." <em>Ἐκεῖνος</em> — John\'s elevated demonstrative for Christ. <em>Τίθημι τὴν ψυχήν</em> = "to lay down the soul/life" — the identical phrase as John 10:11,15,17,18. The act was voluntary and unrepeated (aorist <em>ἔθηκεν</em>).</p><p><strong>καὶ ἡμεῖς ὀφείλομεν ὑπὲρ τῶν ἀδελφῶν τὰς ψυχὰς θεῖναι</strong> — "and we are obligated to lay down our lives for the brothers and sisters." <em>Ὀφείλομεν</em> — moral obligation (G3784), same as 2:6. The cross is not only the ground of forgiveness but the pattern for community life.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>ὃς δ᾽ ἂν ἔχῃ τὸν βίον τοῦ κόσμου</strong> — "whoever has the world\'s possessions." <em>Βίος</em> (G979) — material means of living, distinct from <em>ζωή</em> (spiritual life). <strong>θεωρῇ τὸν ἀδελφὸν αὐτοῦ χρείαν ἔχοντα</strong> — "and sees his brother having need." <em>Θεωρέω</em> = to behold carefully, observe attentively — a present participle of watching, not mere noticing. <strong>κλείσῃ τὰ σπλάγχνα αὐτοῦ ἀπ᾽ αὐτοῦ</strong> — "shuts his compassion from him." <em>Σπλάγχνα</em> (G4698): entrails — the Greek seat of deep emotion and compassion (as English uses "gut" or "heart"). To shut the <em>splancha</em> is to clamp down on the movement of compassion. <strong>πῶς ἡ ἀγάπη τοῦ θεοῦ μένει ἐν αὐτῷ</strong> — "how does God\'s love remain in him?" The question is rhetorical: it cannot.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>μὴ ἀγαπῶμεν λόγῳ μηδὲ τῇ γλώσσῃ</strong> — "let us not love in word nor in tongue." Two instruments of verbal expression — <em>λόγος</em> (the utterance, the content) and <em>γλῶσσα</em> (the tongue, the organ). <strong>ἀλλὰ ἐν ἔργῳ καὶ ἀληθείᾳ</strong> — "but in deed and in truth." The contrast is not between speech and silence but between empty declaration and enacted reality. In Johannine usage, truth is not merely propositional but a reality that must be lived (<em>ποιεῖν τὴν ἀλήθειαν</em>, "doing the truth," 1:6).</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>ἐν τούτῳ γνωσόμεθα ὅτι ἐκ τῆς ἀληθείας ἐσμέν</strong> — "by this we will know that we are of the truth." <em>Γνωσόμεθα</em> (future of <em>γινώσκω</em>) — assurance comes from observing love-in-deed, not from introspection alone. <em>Ἐκ τῆς ἀληθείας</em> — origin again: to be "of the truth" means to have truth as one\'s source. <strong>καὶ ἔμπροσθεν αὐτοῦ πείσομεν τὰς καρδίας ἡμῶν</strong> — "and before him we shall persuade/set at rest our hearts." <em>Πείθω</em> (G3982) — to persuade, convince. We argue our own hearts toward confidence in God\'s presence, using the evidence of love enacted.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>ὅτι ἐὰν καταγινώσκῃ ἡμῶν ἡ καρδία</strong> — "if our heart condemns us." <em>Καταγινώσκω</em> (G2607) — to know against, to judge against; the heart acting as prosecutor against oneself. <strong>ὅτι μείζων ἐστὶν ὁ θεὸς τῆς καρδίας ἡμῶν καὶ γινώσκει πάντα</strong> — "because God is greater than our heart and knows all things." Two arguments: God is greater than the condemning heart in authority, and his knowledge is total. His omniscience is not a further threat but the ground for appeal: comprehensive divine knowledge will not miss the genuine love enacted, even when conscience cannot assess it rightly.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>ἐὰν ἡ καρδία μὴ καταγινώσκῃ</strong> — "if our heart does not condemn us." The positive corollary of v.20. <strong>παρρησίαν ἔχομεν πρὸς τὸν θεόν</strong> — "we have boldness toward God." <em>Παρρησία</em> (G3954) — literally "all-speech" — the freedom of unrestricted speech before God. In 1 John it appears at 2:28 (at the parousia), 3:21 (present prayer), and 5:14 (prayer according to his will). The accusative-of-direction <em>πρὸς τὸν θεόν</em> frames prayer as confident approach, not fearful petition.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>ὃ ἐὰν αἰτῶμεν λαμβάνομεν ἀπ᾽ αὐτοῦ</strong> — "whatever we ask we receive from him." The claim is not unconditional: the ground is given in the <em>ὅτι</em> clause — <strong>τὰς ἐντολὰς αὐτοῦ τηροῦμεν καὶ τὰ ἀρεστὰ ἐνώπιον αὐτοῦ ποιοῦμεν</strong> — "because we keep his commandments and do what is pleasing in his sight." <em>Ἀρεστά</em> (G701, pleasing things) and commandment-keeping together characterize the relational context in which effective prayer operates. Answered prayer is a feature of abiding relationship, not a technique.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>αὕτη ἐστὶν ἡ ἐντολὴ αὐτοῦ</strong> — "this is his commandment" (singular). The plural commandments of vv.22-24 are summed up as one: <strong>ἵνα πιστεύσωμεν τῷ ὀνόματι τοῦ υἱοῦ αὐτοῦ Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ καὶ ἀγαπῶμεν ἀλλήλους</strong> — "that we believe in the name of his Son Jesus Christ and love one another." Two verbs, one command: faith and love as inseparable. <em>Πιστεύειν τῷ ὀνόματι</em> — "to believe in the name" uses the dative of trust — the name carries the person; to trust the name is to trust the one who bears it.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>ὁ τηρῶν τὰς ἐντολὰς αὐτοῦ ἐν αὐτῷ μένει καὶ αὐτὸς ἐν αὐτῷ</strong> — "the one who keeps his commandments abides in him and he in him." The mutual indwelling is stated symmetrically: commandment-keeping → human-in-God abiding → God-in-human abiding. The structure is reciprocal but not equivalent: the human keeps commands; God grants the indwelling. <strong>ἐκ τοῦ πνεύματος οὗ ἡμῖν ἔδωκεν</strong> — "by the Spirit which he has given us." The Spirit (G4151, capitalized — the Holy Spirit, as in the translation decisions) is the tangible evidence of divine indwelling. The gift is a completed action (<em>ἔδωκεν</em>, aorist) with ongoing implications.</p>'
  },
  "4": {
    "1": '<p><strong>μὴ παντὶ πνεύματι πιστεύετε</strong> — "do not believe every spirit." <em>Πνεῦμα</em> (G4151, lowercase here — created or supernatural spirits, including those motivating false prophets). The imperative <em>πιστεύετε</em> with <em>μή</em> = "stop trusting" or "do not habitually trust." <strong>δοκιμάζετε τὰ πνεύματα</strong> — "test the spirits." <em>Δοκιμάζω</em> (G1381) = to test by experience, to examine in order to approve or reject — the verb used for testing metals to determine their genuineness. <strong>ὅτι πολλοὶ ψευδοπροφῆται ἐξεληλύθασιν εἰς τὸν κόσμον</strong> — perfect: "have gone out into the world" and remain there.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>ἐν τούτῳ γινώσκετε τὸ πνεῦμα τοῦ θεοῦ</strong> — "by this you know the Spirit of God." <em>Γινώσκετε</em>: present indicative — a reliable, ongoing criterion for recognition. <strong>πᾶν πνεῦμα ὃ ὁμολογεῖ Ἰησοῦν Χριστὸν ἐν σαρκὶ ἐληλυθότα ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ ἐστίν</strong> — "every spirit that confesses Jesus Christ having come in the flesh is from God."</p><p><strong>ἐν σαρκί</strong> — "in flesh." The accusative <em>Ἰησοῦν Χριστόν</em> is the object of <em>ὁμολογεῖ</em>, and <em>ἐληλυθότα</em> is a perfect active participle: "having come" — a completed arrival whose reality persists. The confession targets proto-Docetic teachers who allowed Christ to be divine but not genuinely incarnate in bodily material reality. The perfect participle is key: the flesh is not a temporary vehicle abandoned before the cross but a completed, enduring fact.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>πᾶν πνεῦμα ὃ μὴ ὁμολογεῖ τὸν Ἰησοῦν ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ οὐκ ἔστιν</strong> — "every spirit that does not confess Jesus is not from God." The object shifts: not "Jesus Christ in flesh" but simply "Jesus" — the particular historical person. <em>Μή</em> + present indicative: any spirit whose ongoing, habitual stance is to not acknowledge Jesus. <strong>τοῦτό ἐστιν τὸ τοῦ ἀντιχρίστου</strong> — "this is (the spirit) of the antichrist." The antichrist\'s spirit is recognizable by this specific christological deficiency. <strong>ἤδη ἐν τῷ κόσμῳ ἐστίν</strong> — "it is already in the world." The eschatological adversary is not only future but presently active.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ ἐστε</strong> — "you are of God." The community\'s origin (<em>ἐκ</em>) is God, contrasted with the false spirits. <strong>νενικήκατε αὐτούς</strong> — "you have overcome them" (perfect: completed victory with ongoing standing). <strong>ὅτι μείζων ἐστὶν ὁ ἐν ὑμῖν ἢ ὁ ἐν τῷ κόσμῳ</strong> — "because greater is the one in you than the one in the world." A comparison between two personal powers: the Spirit of God dwelling in believers (cf. 3:24) and the devil / spirit of antichrist operating in the world. The victory rests not in human resistance but in the superior power of the indwelling Spirit.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>αὐτοὶ ἐκ τοῦ κόσμου εἰσίν</strong> — "they are of the world." The false teachers\' origin and allegiance (<em>ἐκ</em>) is the world. <strong>διὰ τοῦτο ἐκ τοῦ κόσμου λαλοῦσιν καὶ ὁ κόσμος αὐτῶν ἀκούει</strong> — "therefore from the world they speak, and the world listens to them." Three consecutive <em>κόσμος</em> uses: origin, content, audience all share the same sphere. The world\'s receptiveness to the false teachers is itself a diagnostic — if the <em>κόσμος</em> as organized opposition to God welcomes a teaching, that is evidence against its divine origin.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>ἡμεῖς ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ ἐσμεν</strong> — emphatic "we are of God" by pronoun position, contrasted with v.5\'s "they are of the world." <strong>ὁ γινώσκων τὸν θεὸν ἀκούει ἡμῶν</strong> — "the one who knows God listens to us." Receptiveness to the apostolic witness correlates with orientation toward God. <strong>ἐκ τούτου γινώσκομεν τὸ πνεῦμα τῆς ἀληθείας καὶ τὸ πνεῦμα τῆς πλάνης</strong> — "by this we know the spirit of truth and the spirit of error." <em>Πλάνη</em> (G4106) — wandering, error. Two spirits, identified by their relationship to apostolic truth and their audience.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>Ἀγαπητοί, ἀγαπῶμεν ἀλλήλους</strong> — "Beloved, let us love one another." The hortatory subjunctive <em>ἀγαπῶμεν</em> opens the letter\'s sustained theological treatment of love. <strong>ὅτι ἡ ἀγάπη ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ ἐστιν</strong> — "because love is from God." The preposition <em>ἐκ</em>: love originates in God; it is not a human achievement transplanted to God. <strong>πᾶς ὁ ἀγαπῶν ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ γεγέννηται καὶ γινώσκει τὸν θεόν</strong> — "everyone who loves has been born of God and knows God." Two results: born of God (perfect, settled state) and knows God (present, ongoing relationship).</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>ὁ μὴ ἀγαπῶν οὐκ ἔγνω τὸν θεόν</strong> — "the one who does not love has not known God." <em>Ἔγνω</em> — aorist of <em>γινώσκω</em>: "has not come to know." The past-tense negation is comprehensive: there is no knowledge of God in this person\'s history. <strong>ὅτι ὁ θεὸς ἀγάπη ἐστίν</strong> — "because God is love." This is the letter\'s second great identification statement (cf. 1:5, "God is light"). The predicate noun <em>ἀγάπη</em> is anarthrous — identifying God\'s essential character without making love exhaustive of his being. The statement does not say "love is God"; direction matters. Cf. v.16 for the second occurrence.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>ἐν τούτῳ ἐφανερώθη ἡ ἀγάπη τοῦ θεοῦ ἐν ἡμῖν</strong> — "in this the love of God was manifested among us." <em>Φανερόω</em> (aorist) — the same manifestation-verb throughout 1 John (1:2; 3:5,8). God\'s love became visible in a historical event. <strong>ὅτι τὸν υἱὸν αὐτοῦ τὸν μονογενῆ ἀπέσταλκεν ὁ θεὸς εἰς τὸν κόσμον</strong> — "because God has sent his only-begotten Son into the world." <em>Ἀπέσταλκεν</em>: perfect of <em>ἀποστέλλω</em> — a past sending with present effect. <em>Μονογενής</em> (G3439) — "only-begotten" or "unique" — carries both uniqueness and the relational intimacy of the only son. The sending <em>into the world</em> (<em>εἰς τὸν κόσμον</em>) is costly in the Johannine frame where <em>κόσμος</em> is hostile territory.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>ἐν τούτῳ ἐστὶν ἡ ἀγάπη</strong> — "in this is love" — love\'s essence is being defined, not merely illustrated. <strong>οὐχ ὅτι ἡμεῖς ἠγαπήσαμεν τὸν θεόν</strong> — "not that we loved God." Aorist — the focus is on initiative, not ongoing pattern: who acted first. <strong>ἀλλ᾽ ὅτι αὐτὸς ἠγάπησεν ἡμᾶς καὶ ἀπέστειλεν τὸν υἱὸν αὐτοῦ ἱλασμὸν περὶ τῶν ἁμαρτιῶν ἡμῶν</strong> — "but that he loved us and sent his Son as propitiation for our sins." <em>Ἱλασμόν</em> (G2434, second and last occurrence in 1 John; cf. 2:2) — the Son sent to be a <em>hilasmos</em>, a propitiation. Both aorists (<em>ἠγάπησεν</em>, <em>ἀπέστειλεν</em>) frame the prior divine initiative as a single historical complex of love-and-sending.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>Ἀγαπητοί, εἰ οὕτως ὁ θεὸς ἠγάπησεν ἡμᾶς</strong> — "Beloved, if God so loved us." The <em>εἰ</em> + aorist indicative is a first-class condition: the reality is assumed as the basis for inference. <strong>καὶ ἡμεῖς ὀφείλομεν ἀλλήλους ἀγαπᾶν</strong> — "we also are obligated to love one another." <em>Ὀφείλω</em> (G3784) — moral obligation — same as 2:6 and 3:16. The obligation derives from received love of God; it is not a separate ethical principle but the logical output of being loved. Chain: God → loved us → we → obligated to love one another.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>θεὸν οὐδεὶς πώποτε τεθέαται</strong> — "God no one has ever beheld." <em>Τεθέαται</em> — perfect of <em>θεάομαι</em> (G2300), to behold carefully or gaze upon. The same claim as John 1:18 (<em>θεὸν οὐδεὶς ἑώρακεν πώποτε</em>). <em>Πώποτε</em> — "at any time, ever" — emphatic absolute exclusion. Since God remains unseen by direct vision, the love of believers for one another becomes the visible form of his indwelling. <strong>ἐὰν ἀγαπῶμεν ἀλλήλους, ὁ θεὸς ἐν ἡμῖν μένει</strong> — the conditional is real: mutual love is both the sign and the condition of divine indwelling. <strong>ἡ ἀγάπη αὐτοῦ τετελειωμένη ἐν ἡμῖν ἐστίν</strong> — "his love has been perfected in us" (perfect passive: a completed state). God\'s love has reached its goal in the community of mutual love.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>ἐν τούτῳ γινώσκομεν ὅτι ἐν αὐτῷ μένομεν καὶ αὐτὸς ἐν ἡμῖν</strong> — "by this we know that we abide in him and he in us." <strong>ὅτι ἐκ τοῦ πνεύματος αὐτοῦ δέδωκεν ἡμῖν</strong> — "because of his Spirit he has given us." <em>Ἐκ τοῦ πνεύματος</em> — "of/from his Spirit." The construction is partitive: God has given us a portion from his Spirit — not the Spirit divided, but the Spirit given in the mode of gift. Perfect <em>δέδωκεν</em>: the giving is complete and its result stands.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>ἡμεῖς τεθεάμεθα καὶ μαρτυροῦμεν</strong> — "we have seen and we testify." <em>Τεθεάμεθα</em> — perfect of <em>θεάομαι</em>, same verb as v.12 for the unseen God: the apostolic witnesses have seen what ordinary observers cannot. <em>Μαρτυροῦμεν</em> — present: the testimony is ongoing. <strong>ὅτι ὁ πατὴρ ἀπέσταλκεν τὸν υἱὸν σωτῆρα τοῦ κόσμου</strong> — "that the Father has sent the Son as Savior of the world." Perfect <em>ἀπέσταλκεν</em> as in v.9: the sending stands. <em>Σωτῆρα τοῦ κόσμου</em> — the same <em>κόσμος</em> that is hostile to God is also the object of the Son\'s saving mission.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>ὃς ἂν ὁμολογήσῃ ὅτι Ἰησοῦς ἐστιν ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ θεοῦ</strong> — "whoever confesses that Jesus is the Son of God." The confession is specific and public: <em>ὁμολογέω</em> requires verbal, articulated acknowledgment. The content is the identity of the particular historical person Jesus as God\'s Son. <strong>ὁ θεὸς ἐν αὐτῷ μένει καὶ αὐτὸς ἐν τῷ θεῷ</strong> — "God abides in him and he in God." The mutual indwelling formula attached to the confession criterion: Christological confession and divine indwelling are structurally linked.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>ἐγνώκαμεν καὶ πεπιστεύκαμεν τὴν ἀγάπην</strong> — "we have known and have believed the love." Two perfects in sequence: knowing precedes and accompanies believing; both are settled states. The object of believing is <em>τὴν ἀγάπην</em> (the love) — John speaks of believing not just propositions but realities. <strong>ὁ θεὸς ἀγάπη ἐστίν</strong> — the second occurrence of the summit statement (cf. v.8). <strong>ὁ μένων ἐν τῇ ἀγάπῃ ἐν τῷ θεῷ μένει καὶ ὁ θεὸς ἐν αὐτῷ μένει</strong> — "the one who abides in love abides in God and God abides in him." Love, God, and indwelling are identified: to abide in love is identically to abide in God, because God is love.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>ἐν τούτῳ τετελείωται ἡ ἀγάπη μεθ᾽ ἡμῶν</strong> — "in this love has been perfected with us." <em>Τετελείωται</em> — perfect passive, as in 2:5 and 4:12. Love reaching its <em>telos</em> (goal, completion) <em>with us</em> — not merely in God. <strong>ἵνα παρρησίαν ἔχωμεν ἐν τῇ ἡμέρᾳ τῆς κρίσεως</strong> — "so that we may have boldness in the day of judgment." <em>Παρρησία</em> (G3954) — the purpose of perfected love is eschatological boldness.</p><p><strong>ὅτι καθὼς ἐκεῖνός ἐστιν καὶ ἡμεῖς ἐσμεν ἐν τῷ κόσμῳ τούτῳ</strong> — "because as that one is, so also we are in this world." <em>Ἐκεῖνος</em> — Christ. The present tense in both clauses: as Christ is now (in his glorified state), so we are now in this world — not <em>will be</em>, but <em>are</em>. Our identity in the world is already determined by our identification with him.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>φόβος οὐκ ἔστιν ἐν τῇ ἀγάπῃ</strong> — "fear is not in love." The anarthrous <em>φόβος</em>: no kind of fear at all has a place in love. <strong>ἡ τελεία ἀγάπη ἔξω βάλλει τὸν φόβον</strong> — "perfect love casts out fear." <em>Βάλλω</em> (G906) = to throw or cast — an expulsive action, not merely a suppression. <strong>ὅτι ὁ φόβος κόλασιν ἔχει</strong> — "because fear has punishment." <em>Κόλασιν</em> (G2851) — corrective penalty — the only use of this word in 1 John (cf. Matt 25:46). Fear oriented toward punishment is what love expels.</p><p><strong>ὁ δὲ φοβούμενος οὐ τετελείωται ἐν τῇ ἀγάπῃ</strong> — "the one who fears has not been perfected in love." Perfect passive: their love has not been brought to completion; they remain in a state of incompleteness. Fear of punishment and perfected love are mutually exclusive conditions.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>ἡμεῖς ἀγαπῶμεν</strong> — "we love." The verb stands alone — many manuscripts add <em>αὐτόν</em> (him) or <em>τὸν θεόν</em> (God), but the earlier reading leaves the object implicit, giving the statement universal scope: all love flows from a single source. <strong>ὅτι αὐτὸς πρῶτος ἠγάπησεν ἡμᾶς</strong> — "because he first loved us." <em>Πρῶτος</em> (first, in priority) combined with <em>ἠγάπησεν</em> (aorist, completed act): God\'s love was prior in time and in logical order. Human love is not the cause but the response — a re-directed stream from the divine source (<em>ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ ἐστίν</em>, v.7).</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>ἐάν τις εἴπῃ ὅτι Ἀγαπῶ τὸν θεόν</strong> — "if anyone says, \'I love God.\'" This is the sixth <em>if anyone says</em> pattern in the letter (cf. 1:6,8,10; 2:4,6,9). <strong>καὶ τὸν ἀδελφὸν αὐτοῦ μισῇ</strong> — "and hates his brother." <strong>ψεύστης ἐστίν</strong> — "is a liar." The argument from the lesser to the greater: <strong>ὁ γὰρ μὴ ἀγαπῶν τὸν ἀδελφὸν αὐτοῦ ὃν ἑώρακεν, τὸν θεὸν ὃν οὐχ ἑώρακεν οὐ δύναται ἀγαπᾶν</strong> — "the one who does not love his brother whom he has seen cannot love God whom he has not seen." Visibility is the pivot: the seen brother is the available, accessible object of love; if the capacity for love fails there, it cannot exist for the unseen God.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>καὶ ταύτην τὴν ἐντολὴν ἔχομεν ἀπ᾽ αὐτοῦ</strong> — "and this commandment we have from him." <em>Ἔχομεν</em> — present: the commandment is in our possession now. <strong>ἵνα ὁ ἀγαπῶν τὸν θεὸν ἀγαπᾷ καὶ τὸν ἀδελφὸν αὐτοῦ</strong> — "that the one who loves God must also love his brother." The <em>καί</em> (also) ties the two loves together: they are not independent commandments but one linked command. The love of God that does not issue in love of the visible sibling is not the love of the God who is love.</p>'
  }
}


